about 1504","1553":"1553","about 1553":"about 1553","1480":"1480","1505":"1505","Churchstoke, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Churchstoke, Montgomeryshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cadwaladr","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Welsh:  see  Cadwallader  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cadwallader","meanings":["Welsh: from the personal name <i>Cadwaladr</i>, from (the ancestors of) <i>cad</i> ‘battle’ + <i>gwaladr</i> ‘leader’.","History: John Cadwallader (died 1734) came from Pembroke, Wales, to PA in the late 17th century. The name Cadwal(l)ader appears in 18th-century Philadelphia, PA, including Thomas Cadwalader (1707–1799), a physician, and his sons, John (1742–1786) and Lambert (1743–1823), both revolutionary war soldiers."]}]},{"name":"Mawd","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Ferch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferg","meanings":["1  ‘Sharp blade’.","2  ‘Wind’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Mawd Ferch Cadwaladr was born in 1505, in Montgomeryshire, Wales, her father, Cadwaladr ap Hywel, was 28 and her mother, Mallt ferch Ieuan, was 26. She married Owain ap Ieuan. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters."},"et":{"1505–":"1505–Surnud","1505–Female":"1505–Surnud","1505–Male":"1505–Surnud","1415–Male":"1415–Surnud","1436–Female":"1436–Surnud","1553–Male":"1553–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1478–Male":"1478–Surnud","1480–Female":"1480–Surnud","1415":"1415","1436":"1436","1478":"1478","about 1504":"umbes 1504","1553":"1553","about 1553":"umbes 1553","1480":"1480","1505":"1505","Churchstoke, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Churchstoke, Montgomeryshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Wales"},"fi":{"1505–":"1505–Kuollut","1505–Female":"1505–Kuollut","1505–Male":"1505–Kuollut","1415–Male":"1415–Kuollut","1436–Female":"1436–Kuollut","1553–Male":"1553–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1478–Male":"1478–Kuollut","1480–Female":"1480–Kuollut","1415":"1415","1436":"1436","1478":"1478","about 1504":"noin 1504","1553":"1553","about 1553":"noin 1553","1480":"1480","1505":"1505","Churchstoke, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Churchstoke, Montgomeryshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Wales"},"fr":{"1505–":"1505–Décédée","1505–Female":"1505–Décédée","1505–Male":"1505–Décédé","1415–Male":"1415–Décédé","1436–Female":"1436–Décédée","1553–Male":"1553–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1478–Male":"1478–Décédé","1480–Female":"1480–Décédée","1415":"1415","1436"